<span id="v.v.iv.lxvi-p1"></span> <span class="c11"><span
id="v.v.iv.lxvi-p1.1"></span>Chapter 66.—</span>147.  <span
class="c11"><span id="v.v.iv.lxvi-p1.2"></span>Petilianus</span> said: 
"‘Blessed are they which do hunger and thirst after righteousness:  for
they shall be filled.’  To you it seems to be righteousness that you
thirst after our blood."

<span id="v.v.iv.lxvi-p2"></span>148.  <span class="c11"><span
id="v.v.iv.lxvi-p2.1"></span>Augustin</span> answered:  What shall I say
unto thee, O man, except that thou art calumnious?  The unity of Christ,
indeed, is hungering and thirsting after all of you; and I would that it
might swallow you up, for then would you be no longer heretics.

